    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "d5cbe7571829988712fb6a446ee540cf3c3bd7856c245d2f47cb812c39a8129d",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s could prove\\[\\epsilon_n \\gg \\frac{\\log\\log\\log n}{\\log\\log n}.\\]See also [687], [689], and [1200]."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "7ac943e4d0db4b41b612e4ecba4525f5706398a14f2a9ebde3be21fd8e0ae449",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Define $\\epsilon_n$ to be maximal such that there exists some choice of congruence class $a_p$ for all primes $n^{\\epsilon_n}<p\\leq n$ such that every integer in $[1,n]$ satisfies at least one of the congruences $\\equiv a_p\\pmod{p}$.\n\nEstimate $\\epsilon_n$ - in particular is it true that $\\epsilon_n=o(1)$?"
    }
  },
